**Fix 1 — support_io.sch: #PWR019 isolated GND symbol (Net 832)**

**Root cause:** `power:GND` symbol `#PWR019` at sheet position (4500,7200) had zero wires
attached. KiCad 5.1.5 assigns a separate isolated net to any power symbol with no wire
connections, even if the symbol's net name (GND) would otherwise merge it into the global
GND net. Net 832 had one W-type pin (#PWR019) and no power driver → ErrType(3).

**Fix:** Added two wires to connect #PWR019 to J6 pin 4 (UART header GND, sheet position
(4700,6800)):
- `Wire Wire Line 4500 7200 4500 6800` (vertical leg)
- `Wire Wire Line 4500 6800 4700 6800` (horizontal leg to J6 pin 4)

J6 (Conn_01x04_Male) pin 4 computed position verified: P=(4500,6600), matrix (1,0,0,-1),
lib pin at (200,-200) → sheet(4700,6800). Connection is exact, no tolerance gap.

Once #PWR019 has any wire, KiCad merges it into the global GND net (matched by name).
GND has `w`-type drivers from LDO GND pins in power.sch → ErrType(3) clears.

**Note:** J6 pins 1–3 (TX/RX/VCC) remain unconnected — TX/RX wires terminate at x=4100,
J6 pins at x=4700 (600-mil gap). This is a pre-existing design gap, separate from the
ErrType(3) task. Flagged for Phase 5b follow-up or Phase 6 treatment.

---

**Fix 2 — connectors.sch: J1.C50 / VIN net cross-sheet PWR_FLAG (Net 259)**

**Root cause investigation:**

Geometric verification of all 8 VIN stubs against UZEV_Connectors.lib (JX1 VIN pins:
A43, A46, A49, A50, B44, B47, B50, C50). Transform formula: sheet_x = comp_x + lib_x,
sheet_y = comp_y − lib_y (matrix 1 0 0 −1). All 16 checks (8 wire endpoints + 8 GLabel
positions) pass exactly — no geometry bug.

VIN GLabel on power.sch: `Text GLabel 4000 2900 2 50 Output ~ 0 VIN` at (4000,2900).
Wire: `2400 2900 → 4000 2900`. #FLG_N01 PWR_FLAG at (3000,2900) is on this wire. ✓

**Finding — KiCad 5.1.5 per-sheet ERC behavior (project-level gotcha):**

KiCad 5.1.5 ERC evaluates power net driving per-sheet:
- `w`-type component output pins (e.g., LDO output pins) drive nets **globally** — they
  satisfy W-type pins on every sheet.
- PWR_FLAG symbols (also `w`-type) drive nets **locally** — they satisfy W-type pins only
  on the same sheet. A PWR_FLAG on power.sch does NOT satisfy W-type pins on connectors.sch
  for the same named net.

This is why VIN is unique among the 8 power nets on connectors.sch:
- VCCO_HP_65, VCCO_HP_64, FMC_3P3V, MGTAVCC, MGTAVTT: driven by LDO_Fixed_EN output
  pins (w-type, globally propagated) → no ErrType(3) on any sheet.
- VADJ, MGTVCCAUX: share the VCCO_HP_65 net → same global driver.
- VIN: barrel jack J5 Tip pin is passive (P type). Only driver is #FLG_N01 PWR_FLAG on
  power.sch, which is sheet-local. 8 W-type JX1 pins on connectors.sch have no local driver
  → ErrType(3). ERC reports one error citing J1.C50 (one report per undriven net, not per pin).

**Fix:** Added `power:PWR_FLAG #FLG01` at P(10000,8450) on connectors.sch. Initial placement
put the pin at the midpoint of wire `9900 8450 → 10100 8450`. ERC run #2 reported
`Pin 1 (Power output) of component #FLG01 is unconnected` — wire midpoint placement did not
connect the pin. Wire was subsequently split into two segments at (10000,8450) so the PWR_FLAG
pin sits at a wire endpoint:
- `Wire Wire Line 9900 8450 10000 8450`
- `Wire Wire Line 10000 8450 10100 8450`

**Empirical note (flag for KiCad migration):** The requirement that component pins connect
only at wire endpoints (not midpoints) is inferred from ERC run #2 behavior. No primary
source citation (KiCad 5.1.5 manual or release notes) has been located. This behavior
should be re-verified if the project migrates to a different KiCad version.

Component timestamp ID: AABB0001 (unique in project).

